The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Timeout

 Nandikar hosts its 22nd National Theatre Festival in celebration of the dramatic arts, offering theatre lovers of the city a chance to experience 10 days of intelligent, thought-provoking entertainment. Featuring plays for children and adults in several Indian languages like Bengali, Hindi, Kannad and Marathi, as well as in English, it promises to be a virtual melting-pot of contemporary theatre traditions and cultures, bringing together troupes from all over the country and even beyond. To be ceremonially inaugurated this evening at 6, the inaugural programme comprises songs by Buddhadeb Guha followed by Life and Creation, a composite dance presented by Nandikar?s artistes under Sudipto Kundu?s direction. Marten Hedman?s Teater, Stockholm, will then stage The Cat?s Journey (picture above), a puppet-show for children in English, directed by Marten Hedman. It narrates the tale of a brave little girl, who goes on a fantastic journey with a cat, meeting many exciting characters on the way. In the end, they discover that embracing life without fear is supremely important.The festival also includes exhibitions on legendary Indian theatre personalities and children?s socio-cultural profile, a seminar on children?s theatre and the publication of a collection of theatre writings.

